article.headline: Humphrey missed game for undisclosed reasons
article.linkText: Georgia defeats Florida without leading scorer
article.story:
GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Without top scorer Tasha Humphrey,
Sherill Baker had 19 points to lead No. 18 Georgia past Florida
63-38 Thursday night.

Georgia overcame a seven-point deficit without Humphrey, who
made the trip but spent the game on the bench for what coach Andy
Landers said was poor practice effort. She averages 19.2 points and
8.3 rebounds.

Florida (14-12, 5-8 Southeastern Conference), which lost for the
seventh time in nine games, also played without its leading scorer.
Bernice Mosby, who averages 15.5 points and 8.6 rebounds, was
suspended for violating team rules.

She was on the bench during the first half, but left the arena
"to attend to personal issues," coach Carolyn Peck said.

Both players were sorely missed.

Without Humphrey, a 6-foot-3 freshman forward, Georgia struggled
early. The Bulldogs (21-7, 9-4) gave up easy baskets inside,
trailed 17-10 and were down three at the break. They could have
been in a bigger hole, but Cori Chambers hit four 3-pointers and
scored the team's last 12 points of the first half. She finished
with 15 points -- all from beyond the arc.

Georgia turned things around after the break.

Megan Darrah, who didn't take a shot in the first half, made
three consecutive baskets to start a 20-1 spurt that allowed the
Bulldogs to cruise the rest of the way. The Gators missed their
first 15 shots from the field and finished 3-of-22 in the second
half.

Georgia outscored Florida 41-13 in the second half, handing the
Gators their first loss (11-1) when leading at the break.

Darrah finished with 11 points. Baker had 15 points in the
second half, including four layups, a jumper and a 3-pointer to
help Georgia build a 52-32 lead with 4 minutes to play.

Tashia Morehead led the Gators with 14 points and Brittnay Davis
added 13.
